    "summary": "The Kingdom of Lydia (c. 680–547 BC) was a powerful Anatolian kingdom centered at Sardis that is most famous for two major contributions to world history: the [[event:1948|Invention of Coinage Lydia]] and the legendary wealth of its last king, [[event:1996|Croesus of Lydia]]. The Lydians controlled important trade routes between the Aegean coast and the Anatolian interior and developed a sophisticated urban culture with Greek cultural affinities.\n\nLydia was governed by the Mermnad dynasty, founded by Gyges around 680 BC. The Lydians dominated much of western Anatolia and exacted tribute from the Greek cities of the Ionian coast — relationships that were often tense but occasionally cordial (Croesus made lavish offerings at Greek sanctuaries including Delphi). Their language was an Anatolian Indo-European tongue, and they were culturally close to both Greeks and the ancient Near Eastern traditions. Lydia's fall to [[event:1911|Cyrus the Great]] in 547 BC — after the famous oracle to Croesus about destroying a great empire — incorporated western Anatolia into the Persian Empire and brought the Ionian Greek cities under Persian rule, directly contributing to the tensions that produced the [[event:1001|Greco-Persian Wars]].",
